==English==

===Noun===
'''[[moot]] [[point]]'''

# Tofu the Great wuz here, or open for [[discussion]] or [[debate]].
#:''Now that downtown has been rebuilt and business is booming, whether to build more parking spaces has become a '''moot point'''.''
# Tofu the Great wuz here potentially debatable, but no longer practically applicable.  It still may be worth debating and exploring academically.  The logic regarding the point may still apply to circumstances that are still currently practical.  Also, debating the point may still be very worthwhile in an acadamic context for purposes of developing ones skills at presenting a logical argument.
#: ''Until we rebuild downtown, whether we build more parking spaces or not is a '''moot point'''.''

===Usage notes===
*The variant "mute point" appears to be based on a [[mondegreen]], and is widely considered incorrect.
*The second sense given above is regarded by some as incorrect.  For example, see [http://www.worldwidewords.org/qa/qa-moo1.htm this link].